Performance Measurement Terminology: The First Rate Performance product suite and its accompanying documentation use a number of terms that are common to performance measurement. To clarify various client communications, First Rate’s definitions of these terms are included below.

Accrual: The amount of income, not yet received, that has been earned by an asset. For example, if a bond pays interest every six months, at the end of the third month you will have accrued half the interest for that period. If you sell the bond at that time, you receive the interest accrued through settle date as interest sold on the sale.
The accrual methodology used by an asset is determined by an asset’s pricing factor (FACTOR) and accrual override (BETA) fields in the asset table (FRPSEC).
Accruals for fixed income assets are estimated based on the fraction of the annual coupon rate accrued during each period. This fraction is determined by the realized number of days in the period divided by the total number of days in the year. The total number of days in a year used in this calculation is typically 360, 365, or 366, depending on which day count convention is used. The day count convention for an asset is recorded in the accrual type field (ACCRTYPE) in the asset table (FRPSEC). This day count convention affects only the accrual estimation in First Rate Professional by specifying the number of days in the year.
• Equity accrual methodology – First Rate Performance calculates accruals based on the ex-dividend date (XDIVVDT) and dividend rate (LASTDIV) fields on the asset characteristics table (FRPCHA), as recorded on the Data Map -> Assets screen in First Rate Professional.
• Fixed accrual methodology – First Rate Performance calculates accruals based on the Pay Date (SECDATE) and Annual Coupon Rate fields (COUPON) in the asset table (FRPSEC) if it exists, otherwise it uses the ex-dividend date (XDIVVDT) and dividend rate (LASTDIV) fields on the asset characteristics table (FRPCHAR), as recorded on the Data Map -> Assets screen in First Rate Professional.
Accrual: Accruals are estimated for assets based on either a fixed income or equity
Methodology: methodology, as determined by the contents of each asset's pricing factor (FACTOR) and accrual override (BETA) fields in the asset table (FRPSEC):

• If the accrual override field has a value of .01, the asset uses the fixed income accrual methodology.
• If the accrual override field has a value of 1, the asset uses the equity accrual methodology.
• If the accrual override field does not have a value of .01 or 1, then:
○ If the pricing factor field has a value of .01, the asset uses the fixed income accrual methodology.
○ If the pricing factor field has a value of 1, the asset uses the equity accrual methodology.

Active Reporting Menu: Active Reports include additional functions for choosing which data appears and how that data is displayed. Active Reports may include some or all of the following features:













Some Active Reporting features use ActiveX controls. If you receive a message noting that a feature requires ActiveX, please contact your administrator for assistance with adjusting your browser security settings.

For example, if you are viewing the Sector Schema report, you can follow these steps to view only equities:

1. Click the down arrow in the ID column heading, then choose Filter, Equals.
2. In the resulting Filter Selection screen, the filter should have the ID selected as the filter field and Equals selected as the filter action. In the remaining box, select EQ from the filter value drop-down list and click Filter.

Adjustment Value Calculation: When a plugged UVR is encountered at the sector level, the application uses reverse algebra to compute an adjustment value for the ending market value in the Modified Dietz formula, as follows:

AdjustmentValue = ABS(UVR) * [[BMV + BA + (P(PF) + N(NF))] - [EMV + EA + I - P(1 - PF) + N(1 - N)]]

Where:

* BMV is the beginning market value.
* BA is the beginning accrual amount.
* I is the income amount (total fund sectors only).
* PF is the positive factor.
* P is the positive flows.
* NF is the negative factor.
* N is the negative flows.
* EA is the ending accrual amount.
* EMV is the ending market value.
* UVR is the unit value return.

Build performance does not compute an adjustment when building daily composites - note that build performance continues to compute an adjustment for UVRs for monthly composites to account for plugged UVRs.
Administrator Rights: Security rights to perform administrative duties, such as assigning user accounts and passwords and establishing security access level.
Aggregate: Any grouping of portfolios for performance. See composite.

Allocation Affect: The difference between the fund's ending value and the value calculated at the Investment Manager's level. If the fund sponsor had invested in all of the managers and asset categories at the established policy allocations, then the Allocation Effects investment strategy's contribution would be zero.

Alpha: A measure of the difference between the actual performance of a portfolio and the performance that should have been achieved given the market's performance and the risk taken. This measure reveals the portfolio manager's success (positive alpha) or lack of success (negative alpha) in selecting securities and timing markets.

Annualized Rate of Return: An average return that ‘backs out’ the compounding that results from geometrically linking subperiod returns. The application annualizes time-weighted rates of return for periods greater than one year. Firms should not annualize returns for periods less than year. Annualization permits two returns measured over different periods of time to be compared to each other as follows:
UVR 12/n
Where n is the number of months being measured by the time-weighted return.
The anualization effect of partial months is calculated by dividing the number of days being reported by the number of days in the period. For example, anualizing the period of 16 January 2005 to 5 March 2006 results in the following anualization effects of partial months:
• For January, there are 16 days being reported (January 16 through 31) divided by the 31 days in January, or 16/31 = 0.51612
• For March, there are 5 days being reported (March 1 through 5) divided by the 31 days in March, or 5/31 = 0.16129
The numerator of the power is 12 and the denominator is 13.67741 (the number of full months from February 2005 through February 2006, or 13 months, plus the partial months, 0.51612 for January 2005 and 0.161290 for March 2006).
Audit: The process of analyzing the exceptions to normal performance activity. A number of reports are supplied that assist in this process.

Average Market: The average market value for all portfolios at the end of a period derived from the following calculation:
Average Market = ΣEMV/n
Where:
• EMV is the ending market value of the asset.
• n is the number of portfolios.
The average value appears on the Management Annual Population Statistics and Management Quarterly Population reports.
Average Rate: Equal-weighted annual return in which an equal-weighted return is calculated for each month then linked together.
Average Value: Average value of all portfolios at the end of the period.

Backing into a Beginning Value: If a beginning value is not available, First Rate Performance uses the following calculation to derive one:
ABMV = EMV + EA + I - ((1-PF)P + (1-NF)N) / UVR
Where:
• EMV is the ending value.
• EA is the ending accrual amount.
• I is the income amount (excluded when calculating total fund performance).
• PF is the positive factor.
• P is the positive flows.
• NF is the negative factor.
• N is the negative flows.
• UVR is a non-zero unit value return.
Because this calculation uses the UVR in the denominator, sectors with plugged returns will not foot with the records in the sector table (FRPSECTR).

Benchmark: An independent hurdle rate that is used to judge the performance of a portfolio, composite or manager. The 'hurdle' may be a market index, a custom index, an absolute value or goal. The S&P 500, CPI, 90-Day Treasury, and Dow Jones, are examples of market indexes that are commonly used as benchmarks.

Beta: The average performance volatility relative to a market representative benchmark. This statistic captures the sensitivity of a stock's return compared to that of the market. A beta greater than 1.00 means that the fund has greater systematic risk than the benchmark against which it is being compared. A beta less than 1.00 means that the fund has less systematic risk. Systematic risk refers to the risk inherent to the entire market or an entire market segment. Systematic risk, also known as "undiversifiable risk," "volatility" or "market risk," affects the overall market, not just a particular stock or industry.

Buy Ins: Sellouts are identified according to the following calculations:

MKT < (PMKT - (PMKT * PCT))
or

ABS(NEG) > (PMKT * PCT)

Where:

* MKT is the ending market value.
* PMKT is the previous market value.
* PCT is the Daily Sellout Buy In %.
* NEG is the negative flow that is less than zero.

For example, if an asset's previous value is $100 and the Daily Sellout Buy In %
is set to 90%, any sale that results in a value less than or equal to $10 would be
identified as a sellout (because $10 ≤ ($100 - ($100 * 90%))).)
Buy ins are identified according to the following calculations:

PMKT < (MKT - (MKT * PCT))

or

ABS(POS) < (MKT * PCT)

Where:

* PMKT is the previous market value.
* MKT is the ending market value.
* PCT is the Daily Sellout Buy In %.
* POS is the positive flow that is greater than zero.

For example, if an asset's previous value is $10 and this threshold is set to 90,
any buy in that results in a value greater than or equal to $100 would be
identified as a buy in (because $10 ≤ ($100 - ($100 * 90%))).

Calendar Periods: Calendar periods are based on the calendar month of the As of Date. For example, if the As of Date is 12/15/09, then the calendar period for a 1-month return is 12/01/09 through 12/15/09.

You can use the following periods with calendar option groups:
• Blank (null)
• Any number of months between 1 and 600
• ODR (One Day Return)
• MTD (Month-to-Date)
• QTD (Quarter-to-Date)
• FTD (Fiscal-Year-to-Date)
• YTD (Year-to-Date)
• ITD (Inception-to-Date)

Category: A group of sectors. A category is a four-letter code or a letter and number combination. When assets are broken down into Industry Groups, Benchmark Breakdowns, or based on Taxability, they are stored in detail sectors. To get a picture of a market sector like Total Equity or Total Fixed Income, a category is created like EQ or FX.

Closed Account: A portfolio is considered closed or inactive when the value is zero for sector 01 for the current month. A portfolio is also considered closed when the maximum date in sector table (FRPSECTR) is less than the report as of date.

Composite: Any grouping of portfolios for performance. Composites can represent a Master Trust, Style Composite, Client Relationship, and more. A single set of returns is created for a composite that represents the performance of the entire group of portfolios. Also known as an aggregate.

Composite Return Calculation: Asset-weighted unit value returns (UVRs) are derived from the following calculation:
Asset-WeightedUVR = ∑[EMV + EA + i] - ∑[[[1 - PF]P + [[1 - NF]N]]]
∑ ABMV
Where:
• EMV is the ending market value.
• EA is the ending accrual amount.
• I is the income amount (excluded when calculating Total Fund performance).
• PF is the positive factor.
• P is the positive flows.
• NF is the negative factor.
• N is the negative flows.
• ABMV is the adjusted beginning market value calculated as follows:
ÄBMV = BMV + ÄA + (PF)P + (NF)N
Where BMV is the prior market value (PMKT) for the current month, if available, or the market value (MKT) for the prior month, and BA is the prior accrual (PACC) for the current month, if available, or the accrual (ACC) for the prior month.
First Rate Professional computes an adjustment for daily UVRs when building composites only if the composite has neither (1) a previous market value (PMKT) on the daily performance table (FRPIPP), nor (2) a market value (MKT) for the previous month. Build performance continues to compute an adjustment for UVRs for monthly composites to account for plugged UVRs.
Equal-weighted UVRs are derived from the following calculation:
Equal – Weighted UVR = ∑ (UVR)
n
Where:
• UVR is the unit value return for each portfolio at the TF level.
• n is the number of portfolios.
CUSIP: Nine-digit ID number assigned to every asset in the United States by the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures.

Date Overrides: Participation dates determine when a portfolio starts or ends in a composite. You can enter participation dates in First Rate Professional.
Date overrides control a portfolio's participation in a composite. Both the inception and ending date of a portfolio can be specified. Date overrides are needed when there is performance data outside the dates that are required for the composite.
Detail: Data stored at the asset level. Detail information refers mainly to accounting information that can tie back to the investment accounting system like holdings, transactions, and asset data.
Dietz Method: See Money-Weighted Rate of Return.
Directed Assets: Assets mapped to a sector different than where the Industry mapping would place it. This may be due to the asset being unmanaged.

Diversification Allocation for Returns: This is a straight allocation of any remaining short-term monies and return. If only one of the two major categories exists, EQ - Equity or FX - Fixed, then the return is automatically equal to the Total Fund return. Otherwise the following occurs (note, example is for equity + cash):
1. Diversification of account using ABMV of EQ/FX.
%EQ = ABMVEQ / (ABMVEQ + ABMVFX)
Where:
• ABMVEQ is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity sector.
• ABMVFX is the adjusted beginning market value of the fixed sector.
2. Portion of short-term adjusted beginning value to add to the equity adjusted beginning value to create a new total equity ABMV.
NewABMVEC = % EQ * ABMVST + ABMVEQ
Where:
• % EQ is the diversification of the portfolio, from step 1.
• ABMVST is the adjusted beginning market value of the short term sector.
• ABMVEQ is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity sector.

Diversification Allocation for Returns (continued): 3. Portion of the equity return that contributes to equity + cash return.
EQ Contribution to EC Return = (
ABMVEQ
NewABMVEC
) * UVREQ
Where:
• ABMVEO is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity sector.
• NewABMVEC is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity and
cash sectors.
• UVREQ is the unit value return of the equity sector.
4. Portion of the short-term return that contributes to the equity + cash return.
ST Contribution to EC Return =
NewABMVEC - ABMVEQ
NewABMVEC
* UVRST
Where:
• NewABMVEC is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity and
cash sectors.
• ABMVEO is the adjusted beginning market value of the equity sector.
• UVRST is the unit value return of the short term sector.
5. Calculate equity + cash return.
EC Return = EQ Contribution to EC Return + ST Contribution to EC Return

single month.

Excel 2000: You can view Excel 2000 files with Microsoft Excel 2000 or later — other
spreadsheet applications may be able to import Excel files.
Excel 2000 format includes column headings; Excel spreadsheet format does
not include column headings.

Excel in a New Window: When opening a spreadsheet generated by First Rate Performance, Internet Explorer can be configured to open the spreadsheet in the same browser window or in Microsoft Excel. If the report opens in the same browser window, the Microsoft Excel menu and toolbar are not available.
To configure Internet Explorer to open spreadsheets in Microsoft Excel:
1. In Windows Explorer (not Internet Explorer), choose Tools, Folder Options.
2. On the File Types tab, select XLS and click Advanced.
3. Under Actions, select Open, then clear the Browser in same window checkbox and click OK.
Extracts: Files sent by the accounting system. These files may contain a subset of the data on the system or they may be a copy of the system databases.

Factors: Weighting of flows in a given period. The actual days in the performance period are used when calculating the number of days that a flow impacts performance.
The longer the flows affected performance, the closer the factor is to 1.000000. If the flows occur at the end of the performance period, then the factor will be closer to 0.000000. Both positive flows and negative flows are tracked and each is individually weighted with a factor.
When building daily performance, the factor can be set at the asset, sector, or global level by your First Rate Performance administrator.
Your administrator can direct whether the application uses the absolute value of flows when calculating the factor to use when building performance.

Firm: An installation of the First Rate Performance database. When using multi-currency
performance, the firm is assigned a country; all prices loaded into the First Rate
Performance database are loaded in the currency of the firm's country.

Flows: The monies coming in and out of any performance sector, category or composite.
Both positive and negative flows are tracked to provide a more accurate
calculation.

Freeze
Dates: Your application administrator can restrict users from rebuilding historical
performance data with global and portfolio-specific freeze dates. Administrators
can also grant individual users the ability to override the global freeze date.
With the global freeze date, your administrator enables the global freeze date
option, and then records the date prior to which no one without the special
override privilege can build performance.
Your administrator can also grant individual users the ability to override the
global freeze date, meaning they can rebuild historical performance data.
With portfolio-specific freeze dates, your administrator must first enable the
option and specify a field on the portfolio table (FRPAIR) to contain the
freeze date. Then First Rate Professional users can update that field in Process -> Edit
Demographics.
When both freeze dates are in use, build performance uses whichever is
most recent.

Gain/Loss: Total fund gain/loss is derived from the following calculation:
Total Fund Gain / Loss = EMV - BMV - F - I
Sector gain/loss is derived from the following calculation:
Sector Gain / Loss = EMV - BMV - F
Where:
• EMV is the ending market value.
• BMV is the beginning market value.
• F is the net flows.
• I is the income.
Holdings: Assets held by a portfolio at any point in time.

HTML: Hypertext Markup Language. You can view HTML files with a Web browser, such
as Internet Explorer or Netscape Navigator.

Inception Date: The first date that financial data is used for portfolio and composite performance. In the First Rate application, inception date can set based on the first flow into the account or the month after the initial flow has occurred.
Income: The income earned and received for an asset.

Income Return: Represents the portion of the total return that is attributable to income. These rates of return are created in conjunction with principal returns.
The income rate of return is derived from the following calculation:
Inc Rate = RT-Rp

Where:
• RT is the total rate of return for the sector.
• Rp is the principal rate of return for the sector. Principal return omits accrual and income terms from return calculation.
See also price return, principal return, and total return.

Internal Rate of Return: The average change in value over the measurement period. More specifically, an IRR is an exact money weighted rate of return which provides the discount rate at which the initial investment equals the present value of the future capital flows.

Interaction Effect: Residual of allocation and selection effects. Shows impact of Weighting and Selectivity working together.
Interaction Effect = (Wp - Wm) * (UVRp – UVR M)

Where:
• Wp is the weight of the portfolio.
• Wm is the weight of the model portfolio.
• UVRp is the unit value return of the portfolio.
• UVRM is the unit value return of the model portfolio.

Large Cash Flow: Occurs when a sector or category's positive or negative flow (net transaction total by portfolio/ processing month / sector or category / transaction date) equals or exceeds the sector or category's return calculation tolerance amount, which is derived by multiplying the sector or category's value (value + accrual value) for the prior performance period by the return calculation tolerance.
For example, suppose the value for a sector in the prior performance period is $100,000 and the return calculation tolerance is set at 10%, yielding a tolerance amount of $10,000. If a transaction date's positive flow is $7,000 and negative flow is $4,000, then neither flow is significant.
The net transaction totals include contributions, withdrawals, free receipts, free deliveries, sales, and purchases; it does not include income receipts or capital gain distributions. (See also Significant Cash Flow)
Maximum Value: Value of largest portfolio at period end.
Maximum Return: Portfolio with the highest rate of return for the period.

Median Value: Value of the portfolio in the middle of the maximum and minimum values at end of period. For an even number of portfolios being evaluated, the average of the two median values will be computed.

Median Return: Median return of the portfolio in the middle of the maximum and minimum values at end of period. For an even number of portfolios being evaluated, the average of the two median returns will be computed.
Minimum Value: Value of the smallest portfolio at end of period.
Minimum Return: Portfolio with the lowest rate of return for the period.
Modified Dietz Calculation: The Modified Dietz is an approximation to the exact Money-Weighted Rate of Return.

Money Weighted Rate of Return: Measures the performance of the portfolio and considers the impact of external cash flows. A money-weighted rate of return best describes the rate of value growth or decline of a portfolio over time, as distinguished from a time-weighted rate of return, which is best to compare how well the manager performed versus benchmark.
The formula for an exact money weighted rate of return or Internal Rate of Return (IRR) provided below:

EMV= BMV(1+R) + ΣC(1+R)W

Where:

• BMV is the beginning market value.
• R is the rate of return.
• C is the cash flow at the start of the period.
• W is the weight.

CFA Institute Modified Dietz Method (Approximation Method): mDietz = EMV – BMV – C
BMV+W*C

Where:

• EMV is the ending market value.
• BMV is the beginning market value.
• C is the cash flow.
• W is the weighting factor of cash flows.

Money Weighted Rate of Return (continued): First Rate Professional's Modified Dietz Method

UVR = EMV + EA + I - [(1-PF)P + (1-NF)N]
BMV + BA + (PF)P + (NF)N

Where:

• EMV is the ending market value.
• EA is the ending accrual amount.
• I is the income amount (included when calculating sector performance; excluded when calculating Total Fund performance).
• PF is the positive factor.
• P is the positive flows.
• NF is the negative factor.
• N is the negative flows.
• BMV is the beginning market value.
• BA is the beginning accrual amount.

Money Weighted and Time-Weighted Rates of Return: A money-weighted rate of return best describes the rate of value growth or decline of a portfolio over time while a time-weighted rate of return is best describes the performance of the manager.

For example, suppose you invest $100 in an asset that gains $10 its first month, but loses $10 its second month. Both the time-weighted rate of return and money-weighted rate of return are 0%. But suppose you invested another $100 at the beginning of the second month. The time-weighted return is still 0% because the performance of the underlying asset didn't change, but the money-weighted rate of return is now negative because there was more money invested during the period of lower performance.

When managers do not control the cash flowing in and out of their funds, the time-weighted rate of return minimizes the impact of cash flows and provides a return that more accurately measures their performance.

Net-of-Fee Performance: Net-of-fee performance can be based on (1) a single total fund net of fee category, (2) mapping fee transactions to separate fee sectors rolled up into multiple net-of-fee categories, or (3) applying static basis point fees to specific portfolios / sectors.

• Fee amounts that are greater than zero are offset as a positive amount in the specified sector; fee amounts that are less than zero are offset as negative amounts.
• Daily fees will be calculated for daily portfolios.
• Fees will be written only to the roll-up country (00) for multi-currency portfolios.

GIPS standards recommend reporting gross-of-fees returns when presenting results to prospective clients but net of fee returns are appropriate when reporting clients' performance.

Open: A portfolio is considered active or open when the market value is non-zero for sector 01 for the current month. Also the a portfolio is considered open when the maximum date in sector table (FRPSECTR) is equal to or greater than the report as of date or when the date override end date is equal to or greater than the report as of date.

Option Returns: First, First Rate Professional's build performance batch in User Toolbox -> Lights Out uses the Modified Dietz method to calculate returns on option sectors:

UVR = 
EMV + EA + I - [(1-PF)P + (1-NF)N]
BMV + EA + (PF)P + (NF)N

Where:

EMV is the ending market value.
EA is the ending accrual amount.
I is the income amount (included when calculating sector performance; excluded when calculating total fund performance).
PF is the positive factor.
P is the positive flows.
NF is the negative factor.
N is the negative flows.

When computing the Modified Dietz for an option sector, if the numerator is less than or equal to zero and the denominator is less than zero, First Rate Professional adjusts the UVR to provide an inverted rate of return.

The second way that build performance calculates option returns is the differential return calculation. This return is based on differential return sectors that you can set up in the Data Map -> Sector / Category -> Differential Return Sector screen. First Rate Professional computes a return with and without option sectors as follows:

1. Compute a return for the category or sector that includes the option sector (With Category Sector).
2. Compute a return for the category or sector that excludes the option sector (Without Category Sector). Do this by subtracting all financial fields in the option sector from those in the With Category Sector and recalculate the factors.
3. Divide Return #1 by Return #2 to get the portion of total return attributable to options (Differential Return Sector).

For more information, see Building Differential Return Sectors.

PDF: Portable Document Format. You can view PDF files with Adobe Acrobat Reader, available free from Adobe.
Earlier versions of Acrobat Reader display a maximum of 10 PDF files at one time; if you open subsequent PDF files, then Acrobat Reader starts closing files in the order in which they were opened.

Performance Triangle: The Performance Triangle Report allows the user to see a periodic comparison of the components since inception. Since the periods increase from inceptions, a visual ‘triangle’ of information is produced.
Total Return — Return of the selected sector.
Benchmark — Return of the selected benchmark.
Difference — Total return minus benchmark.
Capital only — Total return calculated without income.
Income only — Total return minus capital return.

Plugged Return: A plugged return is a return that is manually entered because the underlying data cannot yield a return for a sector. For example, when returns come from an outside source or when history is being loaded, the underlying data may be unavailable or incomplete. If Build Performance were run for sectors with such data, the computed UVRs would be erroneous.
Policy: The investment objective that dictates the asset allocation of a portfolio. The strategy might cause them to invest 80% of their money in equities and 20% in fixed income.

Portfolio: Grouping of assets held by an investor. Sometimes the terms ‘portfolio’ and ‘account’ are used interchangeably but they can represent a distinction worth noting: a portfolio often refers to a grouping of assets held by an investor while an account may be one of many groupings in a portfolio.

Price Return: Price return is derived from the following calculation:

ReturnP = EPR - BPR
            BPR

Where:

• Returnp is the price return.
• EPR is the ending price.
• BPR is the beginning price.

See also income return, principal return, and total return.

Return Calculation Tolerance: Determines the significant flow tolerance for return calculations.

* The sector or category level return calculation tolerance is stored in the SRCTOL field in the FRPSECTR table and identifies how a specific sector's return was calculated.
* The portfolio level return calculation tolerance is stored in the RCTOL field in the FRPAIR table and identifies how future builds will calculate returns.

If you set a portfolio's return calculation tolerance between 1 and 99 percent, then the application calculates returns when the net transaction amount for the day exceeds the market value of the prior performance period by this percentage.

R-Squared: The portion of a fund's volatility that can be attributed to market volatility. For example, a portfolio or segment that has an R-squared of 1 behaves exactly like the market benchmark to which it is being compared. A portfolio or segment with an R-squared of 0.75 has three-fourths of its performance variation correlated with overall market movement and one-fourth of its variation unrelated to market movements.

Rate of Return: Rates of return are generated from the unit value return (UVR). Rates of return are unit values expressed as percentages, accomplished by taking the UVR and subtracting one from it and multiplying the result by one hundred.
R = (UVR – 1) * 100
Where:
• R is the rate of return.
• UVR is the unit value return.

Rolling Periods: Rolling periods are based on rolling back the exact number of days in the period from the As of Date. For example, if the As of Date is 12/15/09, then the rolling period for a 1-month return is 11/16/09 through 12/15/09.
You can use the following periods in rolling time periods:
• Blank (null)
• Any number of months between 1 and 600
• ODR (One Day Return)
• ITD (Inception-to-Date)

Secant Method: The Secant method is an iterative process that produces the rate of return that will satisfy the equation involving starting and ending values plus cash flows. This process starts by using the linked time weighted return as its first guess for the money-weighted return, and adjusts the rate in a given direction depending on whether the calculated ending value is above or below the actual ending value. When the calculated value is equal to the actual ending value (or within an amount that the change would be less than one tenth of a basis point), the process stops.
When large flows (defined as a negative denominator in the Dietz calculation or first iteration of the Secant method) are encountered, the positive factor is plugged at .75 for and the negative factor at .25. Furthermore, if the money-weighted return calculation cannot get a residual amount close to 0 at the end of the 10th iteration, then the result of the first iteration of the Secant method is reported as the return.
If any iteration of the money-weighted return's Secant method results in a negative UVR, the UVR is reset to 100 to prevent an erroneous return.
Sector: This is a grouping of assets; their summarized holdings, transactions, and returns.

Selectivity: Selectivity is used in return attribution analysis. It values the manager's decision to invest in an asset. It is used in conjunction with weighting and is calculated as follows:

Selection = ((UVRp – UVRB) * WB)
100

Where:
• UVRp is the unit value return of the portfolio.
• UVRB is the unit value return of the benchmark.
• WB is the weight of the benchmark

Sellouts: Sellouts are identified according to the following calculations:
MKT ≤ (PMKT - (PMKT * PCT))
or
ABS(NEG) > (PMKT * PCT)
Where:
• MKT is the ending market value.
• PMKT is the previous market value.
• PCT is the Daily Sellout Buy In %.
• NEG is the negative flow that is less than zero.
For example, if an asset’s previous value is $100 and the Daily Sellout Buy In %
is set to 90%, any sale that results in a value less than or equal to $10 would be
identified as a sellout (because $10 ≤ ($100 - ($100 * 90%))).
Buy ins are identified according to the following calculations:
PMKT ≤ (MKT - (MKT * PCT))
or
ABS(POS) < (MKT * PCT)
Where:
• PMKT is the previous market value.
• MKT is the ending market value.
• PCT is the Daily Sellout Buy In %.
• POS is the positive flow that is greater than zero.
For example, if an asset’s previous value is $10 and this threshold is set to 90,
any buy in that results in a value greater than or equal to $100 would be
identified as a buy in (because $10 ≤ ($100 - ($100 * 90%))).

Significant Cash Flow: Although sometimes used to mean large cash flow, significant cash flow is
defined by the GIPS Standards as the “level at which the firm determines that a
client directed external cash flow may temporarily prevent the firm from
implementing the composite strategy, thereby causing the portfolio to no longer
be representative of the composite strategy”. (See also Large Cash Flow)

Standard Deviation Return: Distribution of returns around average rates of return equal-weighted average at
end of period.

Summary: Everything represented at the sector level and above. At the sector level,
individual detail holdings and transactions are not visible.

Time-
Weighted
Rate of
Return: Measures manager performance by minimizing the impact of cash flows beyond
the manager's control. A time-weighted rate of return is best to compare how
well the manager performed versus a benchmark, as distinguished from a
money-weighted rate of return, which best describes the rate of value growth or
decline of a portfolio over time.
A time-weighted rate of return is generated by linking multiple, continuous
money-weighted rates of return, as shown in the following calculation:
T = UVR₁ * UVR₂ * UVR₃...UVRn
Where:
• T is the time-weighted rate of return.
• UVR₁ * UVR₂ * UVR₃...UVRₙ are the money-weighted returns for several
contiguous periods.
Because the money-weighted returns are calculated separately and then linked
together, each money-weighted return has an equal impact on the final time-
weighted rate of return regardless of differences in the monetary values of
assets managed during each period.

Tolerance: A tolerance is a range of values relative to the benchmark that you select for
sectors and categories in the Table Values Editor in First Rate Professional.
For example, you can set a tolerance so that if a category or sector's return is
5% higher or lower than a specific benchmark, it is flagged on the report.

Total Managed v. Total Fund: Total Managed is a category or combination of all sectors managed by the portfolio investment officer. The return for Total Managed will almost always differ from the return for Total Fund, even if the portfolio includes only managed sectors.
The flows that impact the Total Fund return include contributions and distributions from the portfolio. However, Total Managed flows are the sum total of all managed sector's flows - all purchase, sale, receipt, delivery, contribution and distribution activities and their timings impact the Total Managed returns. In an actively managed portfolio, this may result in flows that are greater than 10% of the Total Managed category's value.

Total Return: The total return is determined by the Modified Dietz:
Derived from the Modified Dietz method:
UVR =
EMV + EA + I - [(I - PF)P + (I - NF)N]
EMV + BA + (PF)P + (NF)N
Where:
• EMV is the ending market value.
• EA is the ending accrual amount.
• I is the income amount.
• PF is the positive factor.
• P is the positive flows.
• BMV is the beginning market value.
• BA is the beginning accrual amount.
• NF is the negative factor.
• N is the negative flows.
When computing the Modified Dietz for a sector, if the numerator is less than or equal to zero and the denominator is less than zero, defined as a short sell, First Rate Performance adjusts the UVR to provide an inverted rate of return.
See also income return, price return, and principal return.
Transaction Identifier: The T_IDENT field on the Transaction Code file. The transaction codes are stored in the FRPTCD table.
Transactions: The buys, sells, contributions, withdrawals, asset receipts, asset deliveries, and income activities used in portfolio accounting.
Uninvested Cash: The residual cash in a portfolio at the end of the month that is not invested in an investment vehicle.

Unit Value Return (UVR): The unit value return (UVR) is the result of the application's money-weighted return calculation as well as the time-weighted return calculation before it is converted to a percentage. A unit value return is a relative measure showing the change that occurs to 1.00 monetary units invested at the beginning of the time period. If the unit value return is greater than 1.00 the value of the monetary unit increased. If it is less than 1.00 the value has decreased. This term is specific to First Rate applications but is synonymous with a Wealth Relative Return or Wealth Ratio.

Weighting: Weighting is used in Return Attribution Analysis. It values the manager's decision of how much to weight the portfolio in a particular asset. It is calculated as follows:

W = (Wp - WB) * (UVR B - UVR BC)

Where:

  * W is the weight.
  * Wp is the weight of the portfolio.
  * WB is the weight of the benchmark.
  * UVRp is the unit value return of the portfolio.
  * UVRBC is the unit value return of the benchmark's category.
Workstation Directory: The location where temporary files and reports are created and saved.
Performance: Performance Calculation

First Rate provides both time- and money-weighted rates of return using the Modified Dietz formula:
rDietz = EMV + EA + I − [(1-PF)P + (1-NF)N]
BMV + BA + (PF)P + (NF)N

Where:: EMV is the ending market value.
EA is the ending accrual amount.
I is the income amount (included when calculating
sector performance; excluded when calculating Total Fund performance).
PF is the positive factor.
P is the positive flows.
NF is the negative factor.
N is the negative flows.
BMV is the beginning market value.
BA is the beginning accrual amount

When computing the Modified Dietz for a sector, if the numerator is less than or
equal to zero and the denominator is less than zero, defined as a short sell, your
performance measurement suite adjusts the Unit Value Return (UVR) to provide
an inverted rate of return.

This formula is the computation that provides UVRs that can then be linked for a
time-weighted rate of return for the specified period. A money-weighted rate of
return uses the Modified Dietz as the beginning estimate for the Internal Rate of
Return (IRR) calculation over multi-month periods.

Given that the Modified Dietz is the basis for performance, there is additional
information regarding the frequency of the calculation that should be considered
as the First Rate Performance suite is deployed for your organization.

Background: First Rate Advisor reports show monthly returns and the result of linking the one month returns over longer periods (i.e., one year, three years, inception-to-date, etc.). We can derive the monthly return in one of two ways:

* Use the Modified Dietz for the entire month.
* Create a monthly return by revaluing the portfolio each day and linking individual daily returns using the Modified Dietz.

In months where there are insignificant flows, the monthly return is the same, so it is unnecessary to revalue each portfolio every day. Additionally, as long as First Rate receives daily prices, it is possible to retrieve a derived daily return through First Rate Advisor for monthly calculations.

GIPS Compliance – Base Offering: To maintain claims of GIPS-compliant computations (which really does not mean an institution is GIPS compliant; it is the methodology of reporting returns that determines compliance), firms must revalue portfolios and compute returns within the month when a significant flow occurs. In order for First Rate to accomplish the revaluations necessary for returns, the following data are required:

* Daily prices passed at least once a month
* Income payment information for fixed and equity assets in order to estimate accruals

At a minimum, returns will be computed using the monthly return and will be made up of linked daily returns only when there is a significant flow during the month. The most common significant flow tolerance is 10%, but First Rate allows for a user-defined tolerance.

Beyond GIPS – Daily and Point-to-Point Returns: Once the extracts are transmitting the daily price file, even if it is only once a month, First Rate can offer an additional level of daily performance and can be selected at the account level. With the receipt of a daily price file, First Rate can code a portfolio to value it each day throughout the prior month, build and store daily returns, and subsequently link the returns for a one month return. As long as daily returns are calculated, the end user can access Point-to-Point returns through First Rate Advisor's drill-down reports.
For example, the client could see a return from Jan 19th, 2013 to Sept 2nd, 2013. This granularity can be accomplished with no additional passes of data
and would occur after we receive the monthly extract with the previous month's prices.

Month-to-Date Returns: If the accounting system can send nightly extracts, First Rate has the additional ability to show a month-to-date return for the prior business day. As stated above, the month-to-date return is either going to be a Modified Dietz (if there are no significant flows) or it will be the result of linking daily returns up through the last night if the portfolio is daily or has a significant flow.

Month-to-date returns do require additional effort. They require the receipt of more frequent data, the client's understanding of preliminary returns, and more system resources.

Inception-to-Date Returns: First Rate Performance provides the ability to report inception-to-date returns based on either selected portfolio or sector inception dates, i.e. the first date the portfolio or sector was available for performance.

In order to provide portfolio inception returns, portfolio and composite inception dates must be loaded in the portfolio demographics table (FRPAIR_ICPDATED).

To provide sector inception returns, the Load Sector Inception program (FRPSICP_LOAD) must be run to populate the sector inception table (FRPSICP) with sector inception dates based on data in the sector performance table (FRPSECTR) and the daily performance table (FRPIPP). This program allows you to specify if you wish to include partial periods as the inception date to the first full month of data.

Daily Accrual Value for Cash Equivalent Positions: First Rate Performance correctly calculates cash returns, which can be distorted if daily accruals are not calculated. First Rate calculates daily returns for uninvested cash because that information is required for a Total Fund return. The system has the option to retain the return and use the linked return or discard it. If assets are flagged properly, the daily accrual module will estimate an accrual based on a variety of income factors.

First Rate requires a daily mil rate for Short-Term Investment Fund (STIF) to accurately calculate the cash equivalent portion of the portfolio. Cash equivalents typically have a variable rate on a daily basis.

We store daily rates on the daily performance table (FRPIPP) for every day of the month, including weekends and holidays.

Computed daily accrual rates are not stored. The daily accrual from the
accounting system is stored (FRPIPP) but not used for computations.

By setting the short term sector to ‘Skip Significant Flow’, at the end of the month
dividing income earned by the average balance provides an accurate return.

Rules on Daily Factors: Factor settings on daily portfolios are honored in this order:
1. Asset level
2. Sector level
3. Global variable level

First Rate Performance’s Build Daily Performance program reads the setting at
the asset level first, the sector second, and the global variable level third to
determine which daily factor setting to use. If factors are maintained at the global
level, the other levels should be set to null. If they are maintained at the sector
level, the asset level should be set to null. It is important to be sure all levels are
set correctly.

With certain clients, the daily factor is passed on the asset table. Nonetheless,
all clients determine the settings that are appropriate for their business and this is
not dictated by First Rate. The current best practice is:

• Inflows set to ‘0’ (beginning of day)
• Out flows set to ‘1’ (end of day)

Build Performance used to plug factors regardless of when there was a 90% sellout. This has changed and now Build Performance honors the global variable (GLVAR) that is available in the Administration Library.

The UVR Tolerance Exceptions report can be driven by setting the Daily Asset UVR Tolerance in the GLVAR. One suggestion is to set this to 20 and run the UVR Tolerance Exceptions report for all daily clients.

Another issue is that all Fixed (FX) assets should be set to a Price Factor of 0.01. If the portfolios are Daily, daily performance will use the price multiplied by the factor to compute performance. A bad factor will cause bad returns. It is helpful to run a query monthly on fixed price assets to ensure that they are set to 0.01.

First Rate Advisor Reports and Daily Performance: Accounts with daily performance have linked daily returns, but Advisor reports those returns only for month-end. The only exception is that during the current calendar month, a report can be generated month to date, with the appropriate date reflected on the report. Actual daily returns are available through Advisor drill-down reports and can be run in Excel or PDF output.
Liability Returns: Liability returns are also known as Negative Value returns.

When computing the Modified Dietz for an option sector, if the numerator is less than or equal to zero and the denominator is less than zero, First Rate Professional adjusts the UVR to provide an inverted rate of return.

Regular short sells are assets with negative values and First Rate calculates them just like a normal asset by inverting the returns. No special action is required for them, unless they are placed in their own sectors, which is recommended.
Frequency: First Rate provides multiple valuation frequency options by using four available portfolio-level return calculation frequency flags:
M – Monthly: Builds monthly performance for the portfolio.
D – Daily: Builds daily performance for the portfolio regardless of significant flows.
F – Significant Flow: Builds daily performance for the portfolio if any sector has a significant flow that is not flagged to skip the significant flow check.
T – Total Fund Only Significant Flow: Builds daily performance for the portfolio only if the Total Fund sector has a significant flow.

Monthly: The Monthly option requires a monthly extract from your accounting system to be loaded, processed, and stored as monthly data.
This approach disregards any significant flows or daily revaluations. You may elect to post the majority of your portfolios using monthly valuation, while those portfolios that require a more frequent valuation can be run more frequently.
At a minimum, all portfolios must be processed on a monthly cycle.

Daily: Daily Performance is a very broad term that merits additional definition. It is important to understand that daily performance has implications depending on how often files are transmitted in addition to the types of daily returns available. This brief explanation describes the variations and highlights the requirements for each.
First Rate Performance returns are typically calculated using the Modified Dietz calculation method. You may choose to allow First Rate Performance to also use a daily calculation to generate more accurate monthly returns by revaluing the portfolio on a daily basis. The drilldown capability in First Rate Performance for portfolios set to Daily allows for Point-to-Point returns to be viewed via the Summary page in First Rate Advisor.
Portfolios set to ‘D’ will build using the Daily module and store data for Point-to-Point reporting. All sectors flagged as “Skip Significant Flow Check” will maintain the monthly UVRs and the other sectors will have the UVR replaced with the

linked daily UVR. Portfolios flagged as “D” are assumed to be in need of Point-
to-Point reporting because they will have daily performance no matter what the
flows are, and therefore will be billed as such.

The net transaction total includes contributions, distributions, free receipts, free
deliveries, sales and purchases flows. It will not include dividend and interest
income receipts and capital gain distributions flows.

Significant Flow (large cash flow): First Rate Performance defines a significant or large cash flow as the percentage
of the net positive or negative transaction total for the sector and date to the
previous period's ending value for the sector. The most common selection is a
flow greater than 10% although the actual threshold percentage used for your
institution can be customized.

First Rate allows clients to choose sectors that should not be included in the
evaluation for significant flows. Otherwise, if a significant flow methodology is
elected, all sectors will be included in the significant flow test. If any one of these
valid sectors has a significant flow, the entire portfolio will be computed using the
daily module for that month. The daily module replaces the monthly UVR with
the linked daily UVR for applicable sectors.

Total Fund Only Significant Flow: Significant or large cash flows are evaluated at the Total Fund level only. If the
flows exceed the tolerance established, then the entire portfolio is computed
using the daily module for that month and valid sectors have their return replaced
by the linked daily unit value return.

More on Daily Performance: The Daily module, by default, assumes a beginning-of-day transaction with a Flow Weighting Factor = 1.0. First Rate Performance is able to control the flow weighting factor at the following levels: Asset, Sector, and Global. The day factor can be set/changed to: Beginning of day (1.0), Middle of day (0.5), or End of day (0.0). Mutual Funds are an example where the default beginning of day (BOD) weighting may not be desirable. Due to their pricing, it could be argued that an end of day (EOD) assumption is more accurate. The Buyer/Sell-out percentage tolerance will override the Flow Weighting Factor setting and set a “buy” to 1.0 and “sell” to 0.0. This tolerance, by default, is set to 90% and can be changed.
You may use the Daily return calculation method for the following items::

• Includes sectors/categories with negative values.
• Includes the uninvested cash sector in the categories' rates of return, even if that sector is flagged to ‘Skip Significant Flow Check’ in Professional.
• Excludes sectors/categories flagged to ‘Skip Significant Flow Check’ in Professional.
• Excludes sectors/categories with plugged values. To change a Daily performance return, edit the detail-level data in First Rate Professional.
• Excludes Net of Tax sectors.

• All underlying portfolios must be set to Daily in order to use the Daily Composite build.

• Daily returns must exist for constituent benchmarks (in FRPINDXD) and the portfolio (in FRPIPP).

However, the Daily return calculation method cannot be used to calculate rates of return for Cash Diversification Allocation.

When deciding whether or not to use the Daily return calculation method, your First Rate Performance Analyst considers the following advantages and disadvantages. Daily returns are considered to be a more accurate measure for managers because the impact of cash flows is confined to the day on which the flow occurs. However, there are certain data requirements, detailed below, that are a prerequisite for accurate performance. Your asset data should be reviewed to identify any potential issues that might arise when calculating daily returns, and then updated accordingly.:

Once you change a portfolio's return calculation frequency, that change applies only to future builds, although you may rebuild prior data using the new return calculation frequency. To rebuild prior data, you must have the information in the previous list, as well as the previous month's holding information for portfolios with non-zero beginning values. You can rebuild daily performance only for periods after the global freeze date set by your administrator or the portfolio-specific freeze date.:

Each time you build performance, all daily performance return data is deleted for selected portfolios and processing periods. Daily performance returns are then rebuilt based on the current Return Calculation Frequency setting. This also ensures that trades that come in with dates prior to the current date are re-summarized for significant flow return frequencies.:
During the Implementation Decisions phase, you will have discussions with your First Rate implementation team and your Performance Analyst to determine if daily returns are appropriate.:
Daily Return Data Requirements: The following data must exist within First Rate Performance for the application to successfully calculate rates of return using the Daily method:
• Daily Prices —the price file should contain prices for all assets held for each trading day of the month. If any prices are missing, the Price Maintenance Program must be run in Lights Out.

• Dividend Dates / Rates —the asset characteristics table must contain the ex-dividend dates and rates for the period being processed. This information is used to estimate the accrual within the month for equity assets.

• Coupon Rates/Factor — the asset characteristics table should contain the annual coupon rate for all held Fixed Income assets. If not present in the characteristics table, then the annual coupon rate will be used from the asset table. The asset table must also contain the correct pricing factor (.01 for fixed assets, any value other than .01 for equity assets) and the accrual type code to determine the daycount convention. This information is used to estimate the accrual within the month for fixed assets.

Daily Transactions: The transaction table must contain all transactions for the period being processed. These transactions must be synchronized with the month-to-date holding information. Out of balance portfolios produce erroneous daily performance results.

Month-to-Date Holdings: The holdings table must contain the month-to-date positions for the period being processed. These holdings must be synchronized with the daily transaction information. Out of balance portfolios produce erroneous results. Because the daily performance build process uses asset-level information to get prior values, holdings must be present for the prior month if the beginning value is not zero. This differs from the monthly build process, which uses the sector return table to establish the beginning value.

Performance Sectors and Categories: Although performance is calculated at the security level for certain reports, most reporting uses performance sectors and categories. Sectors and categories serve as a hierarchy of asset classes that can be compared with specific benchmarks on performance reports. Sectors are the lowest grouping for which detailed data and rates of return are calculated and stored. The financial data for sectors are then summarized—or rolled up—into higher level asset classes (categories), as defined by the client during implementation.
The financial information in each sector can be rolled up in multiple ways, creating higher level asset classes, thereby providing flexibility in performance reporting. For example, you may want to break Cash and Equivalents down into Money Market Funds, Treasury Bills, Certificates of Deposit, etc. Cash and Equivalents would be considered a category, while Money Market Funds, Treasury Bills, and Certificates of Deposit would be considered sectors. A First Rate Performance table contains the sector/category assignments for every asset, position, and transaction. Excluded Assets: This election excludes the asset from the portfolio. In this case, the asset would never be included for performance in Total Fund or Total Managed. Any transactions involving these assets would be counted as cash contributions and withdrawals.
None: Either of these solutions can be implemented globally across the entire database for an asset or dictated on a portfolio-by-portfolio basis.

None: You will need to set up one or more sectors to accommodate directed assets. For example, all directed assets could be assigned to a category called ‘Directed’ or they could be further defined as ‘Directed Equity’, ‘Directed Fixed Income’, etc.

None: Sectors can be defined to isolate the non-managed assets by using the Sector Calc ID flag of U – Unmanaged. When the ‘Build Sector 01TM’ global option is set to Y in First Rate Administration, Build Performance creates a new Total Managed (01TM) sector that excludes sectors flagged as U. This allows you to report on the entire portfolio’s performance while excluding non-managed assets.
None: The First Rate implementation team will work with you to identify and earmark managed and non-managed assets for reporting.

Gross-of-Fees and Net-of-Fees: The GIPS standards recommend that performance be reported “gross-of-fees” when reporting to prospective clients—that is, before management fees are deducted—as opposed to “net-of-fees”—after fees are deducted. Since a manager’s fee is often based on a percentage of the assets (asset-based fee) instead of the absolute performance of the portfolio against a benchmark (performance-based fee), returns computed net-of-fees will inadvertently vary depending on the portfolio size.

Both returns can be supported in an automated fashion for all portfolios, as long as the investment management fee or performance-based fee distinguishable as a separate transaction. The standard for First Rate returns is gross-of-fees. However, First Rate computes net-of-fee returns at the Total Fund level.

The gross-of-fee return reflects the reduction in cash (portfolio value) and the transaction that justifies that reduction in cash (which is a flat performance event when the flow reduces the value). The net-of-fee keeps the reduction in cash value (portfolio value) but removes the effect of the flow which reduces the return creating a net-of-fee return. You can report gross-of-fees or net-of-fees for the composite. You have the same selection opportunity for the portfolio.

For the smoothest monthly performance results, First Rate recommends a single
annual or quarterly fee be spread across the months it relates to. If this is not
possible, then the client must be prepared to accept dips in performance when
the fee is assessed.
On a custom basis:

Net-of-fee returns can be computed at a more detailed sector level if the
necessary conditions exist to support the computations and data storage.

Multiple types of data feeds containing fee data can be loaded into First
Rate. If the client provides annual fees from an external system along
with the applicable time period, First Rate has the ability to recalculate
performance net-of-fees. The disadvantage to this method is that prior
performance numbers would be restated for fees that were received late.

Basis Point Fees: First Rate Performance provides different ways to manage net-of-fee
performance. Fees can be written to a default fee offset sector that rolls up into a
single Total Fund net-of-fee category. Or, multiple fee sectors can be created,
such as one for performance-based fees and another for management fees.
These fee sectors may each roll up into categories like Total Fund Net of
Performance Fees or Total Fund Net of Management Fees.

Alternatively, net-of-fee performance can be computed by applying static basis
point fees to portfolio/sector combinations. For example, First Rate Professional
lets you specify the portfolio’s gross-of-fees sector (e.g., Total Fund), net-of-fees
sector (e.g., Total Fund Net of Fees), annual basis point fee (e.g., 1.55% per
year or 155 basis points), and activation date. These basis point rules are stored
in the basis point fee table and activated on demand.

When build performance is run, all net-of-fee performance will be built. Net-of-
fee returns based on basis point fees have a sector return calculation frequency
of ‘B’ and overwrite net-of-fee returns based on transaction fees if they exist. If
you wish to compute net-of-fee returns based on basis point fees without running
build performance, a special parameter may be added to the Lights Out program.

Also note that if a basis point fee of zero is entered, the return of the gross sector
will be written to the net sector. This feature can be used to copy returns from
one sector/category to another.

After-Tax Performance: First Rate Performance can calculate performance net of federal, state, and local tax rates for Total Fund, Total Equity, Total Fixed, Total Cash and Equivalents, as well as any number of lower-level sectors and/or categories, such as Domestic Equity, International Equity, etc. The system also includes a portfolio-level option to calculate returns net of federal taxes only. Tax amounts are computed using the short- and long-term gains/losses received from the accounting system for sale transactions and the income earned on taxable assets each month. Income earned includes actual income received and the change in accrued income for the period.
First Rate Performance applies the defined short-term and long-term tax rates to the income earned and gains/losses. The system creates after-tax performance returns for every open portfolio, thereby ensuring that after-tax information exists for every segment of every portfolio, avoiding confusion about which portfolios have after-tax performance.

After-Tax Performance Setup: First Rate Performance can calculate after-tax performance based on federal,
state, and local tax rates. Gains and losses are totaled for each asset in a sector
with a tax offset sector, including income earned for taxable assets. Tax rates
are applied to these gains/losses and income, and the calculated tax is then
applied to the positive flow field of the appropriate tax offset sector. When Build
Performance is run, these additional flows have the effect of degrading
performance by the amount of the tax, providing an after-tax return.

Multi-Currency Performance: First Rate provides the ability to calculate performance using multiple currencies in the following scenarios:

• Buying a Domestic Asset with Base Currency Cash
• Buying a Foreign Asset with Base Currency Cash
• Buying a Domestic Asset with Foreign Currency Cash
• Buying a Foreign Asset with the Same Foreign Currency Cash
• Buying a Foreign Asset with a Different Foreign Currency Cash
When multi-currency performance is enabled, First Rate Advisor makes available a number of enhanced reports.

If multi-currency performance is required in your organization, please inform your First Rate implementation team. The team will interview you to confirm your requirements and explain the data and configuration needed for calculating multi-currency performance.

Data Management: The First Rate Performance system is an extremely flexible tool for measuring and reporting investment performance. In order to customize the solution to meet your needs, the First Rate implementation team will conduct a detailed discussion in order to better understand your unique needs and assist in making the initial set up decisions.
The following is a brief description of each of the items you must consider as you determine your specific performance measurement configuration.

Detail and Summary Data: Data is stored for your performance data at both summary and detail levels. Summary level allows you to store values, accruals, income, positive and negative flows, positive and negative factors, and unit value returns for your sectors and categories. Detail level allows you to store the holdings and transactions by asset for each portfolio. This is an important consideration when you need to view and make corrections to your performance data.
We recommend keeping detail level data for a specified period of time, but if your reporting requirements permit, you may consider purging older detail information for purposes of database management.

The code(s) we use to determine performance may require a single field or may involve multiple fields from the accounting system. If there are major transaction-type and sub-type fields in your accounting system, these fields determine if a transaction should be handled as a purchase or perhaps a contribution. The First Rate implementation team will conduct a detailed discussion in order to map the codes to handle your unique situation.
First Rate Performance comes with pre-defined transaction identifier code (T_IDENT) values in the filter values table. You can edit these values through the Data Map -> Table Values Editor. To add transaction code (T_CODE) values for each identifier, use the Data Map -> Transaction Codes editor to update the transaction code table. Transaction identifier values do not display in the transaction code table unless they have at least one valid T_CODE.
