Your First Rate implementation team will review a spreadsheet form with sample
entries describing methods for defining transaction effects to First Rate
Performance. The information below will assist you in completing that form. You
may also add fields and information you think will be helpful.

Any ‘general use’ transaction codes used for cash or asset-related activities that are difficult to classify will be potential issues when processing data. Each transaction should serve only a single performance purpose. We require enough information from the system to identify that single effect in order to get the best performance result without scrubbing. The client is responsible for identifying to First Rate all the possible codes and identifiers that should distinguish different types of transactions for performance purposes.

Financial Fields: Depending on the accounting system, multiple financial fields are sometimes used to perform different accounting activities. Examples of these are the Principal, Income, and Carry amounts. In order to get the correct performance effect, we may need to handle the income separately as income to the portfolio or we might need to net the two fields together to get the appropriate performance effect.

Transaction Effect: Part of the discussion regarding transactions is specific to the accounting effect of the transaction. For example, First Rate needs to know if the sign for a transaction is positive or negative and if there is an impact to un-invested cash. You may also need to indicate if the sign for the transaction is assigned by some other process.

Reversals: First Rate will need to understand your method of handling reversals during the measurement period. It is important that these kinds of transactions are handled properly on the extract. We do not want reversals suppressed from the extract if the original transaction was in a prior period. However, during a single extract period, an original transaction and reversal could be suppressed altogether or both could be sent and handled properly in the performance system. Additional discussions on reversals will be part of the implementation process.

Corporate Actions: Corporate actions can often have an adverse effect on performance unless some additional editing is done. Please notify First Rate or indicate on the table if you have any coding on your transactions that would help surface corporate action transactions for proper handling.

Inception Month for Performance: First Rate Performance will attempt to compute a rate of return on the first month data is received for a portfolio. You have the option of using a utility within First Rate to ignore the first partial month of data and use the first full month to be the portfolio inception.
The return computed during the first month makes use of the flow timing and actual flows available during that month. Performance results vary based on whether this portfolio is actually being funded during this month, at the end of the month, or the beginning. The following reports can assist you in surfacing portfolios that might require special review and handling:

• Rate Warnings audit research report
• New and Closed Portfolios standard report
• Asset Summary Review audit research report

A valid inception month for a portfolio is a non-zero return or a plugged return from a historical conversion. During your implementation you may also provide a file of inception dates to use that will override any inception date that First Rate might compute.

Frequency of Transmitting Accounting Data: Data should be transmitted to First Rate at least on a monthly basis. The client may elect to transmit files more frequently due to the large volume of data associated with monthly processing. More frequent loading balances the process over the entire month and allows for pre-month-end auditing, which expedites the month-end process.

When month-to-date performance is required, all files must be transmitted to First Rate on a daily or weekly basis, such as portfolio information, cash balances, holdings, transactions, and asset / price information. The transaction file could contain all trades that settled since the prior transmission, plus any pending trades as of that day. Transmission of data on the trade date is preferred.

For volume considerations alone, it is not necessary to transmit all files to First Rate. In order to reduce data volume, the transaction file would be required that contains only the trades that settled since the prior transmission, plus any pending trades as of that day.

The disadvantage to transmitting daily files as opposed to monthly files centers around transaction adjustments. It is understood that during any given month transactions are being entered, reviewed, and adjusted. A monthly extract is usually structured in such a way that the various adjustments of a transaction can be washed out and sometimes even ignored so only the final transaction is delivered to First Rate. However, if we capture a transaction on a particular day in the month and it is adjusted one or more times later in the month, we need enough information in the transaction file that allows First Rate to identify and modify the original trade.

You may want to consider how far into a new month of performance you want to permit backdating and adjustments of trades. There is no standard for these updates. A client may choose to backdate through the first three business days, end of first week, middle of the month, or up to the end of the following month. The prior month's performance is subject to change each time data is loaded that permits backdating.

Requirements:: The transaction must be sent to First Rate each time it is adjusted.
A unique field should be placed on adjusted transactions so they can be handled in a different manner.
The transactions must all have unique transaction identifiers on them so the original and adjusted transaction can be matched up in the First Rate system and the adjusted transaction applied.

Lights Out Processing and Reporting: First Rate Professional provides Lights Out batch processing and reporting that can be defined and scheduled to run at a specified time, either as a background process, or locally from the user's workstation. Processing in the background allows the user to continue with other functions within the Professional application.

• Loading historical data, inception dates, sector inception dates, or differential return sectors
• Building performance, benchmarks, and composites
• Flagging audit exceptions
• Maintaining prices and accruals
• Performing extracts
• Assigning portfolio, sector, and benchmark report colors
• Viewing status reports and processing logs

Security access assigned by your First Rate Performance administrator determines the functions available to individual users. Your administrator may also restrict certain date ranges and portfolios from Lights Out processing, based upon global and portfolio freeze dates. Your First Rate implementation team will discuss your Lights Out reporting options.

Number of Users: To provide you with the best training and processing experience, The First Rate implementation team will ask you about the number and location of your users. We will need this information to accurately scale your system environment, define your remote access needs, and provide secure access to your reports.

Auditing Returns and Common Return Issues: First Rate relies on quality client accounting data in order to produce accurate returns. If there are consistent issues that prevent the timely computation of reasonable returns, First Rate looks first to the client to correct processes, data, or the accounting system extract. If the client is unable to make the corrections in a timely manner, they will be asked to fund a custom program to repair the accounting issue and increase the release of timely, accurate returns.
A return is the result of the Modified Dietz. The more accurate the data is, the more accurate the return. Therefore, we follow a standard process to ensure a return is reasonable based on the comparable market benchmarks and client data available. As part of our service, we try to help identify common data and accounting problems that cause questionable returns. In a First Rate-client relationship, the client assumes ownership for the quality of the accounting data that might impact a return. Therefore, an amount provided by the client that is marginally inaccurate may not trigger a return audit, though it could still be considered inaccurate.
Troubleshooting Returns:

Cause of Inaccurate Returns: Accruals out of sync with income payments.
Accrual is not computed and the income payment is late.
Late paying income. Income that is received after underlying asset is sold. This is usually a problem in a sector that has sold out of all its holdings or holds very few assets.
Incorrect coupon and dividend payment information. This condition impacts daily sub-period returns. Current month dividend information for equities and the ex-dividend date along with coupon rate for fixed income. The monthly security characteristics table should contain the coupon rate for all fixed income assets. If not present in the characteristics table, then Yield will be used from the security table.

Possible Solutions: Recommend global accrual change to adjust month-end accrual amount when possible.
Leave as-is, because placing the income in the month it occurred restates published returns.
Alternative is for extract not to send this income.
Accounting system is source for income payment information
is source for income payment information.

Cause of Inaccurate Returns: Incorrect prices or lack of daily prices on assets. The security file must contain the correct factor: .01 for fixed income assets, any value other than .01 for equity assets. This impacts ability to revalue portfolio for large flows or daily performance. First Rate relies on the accounting system or other system of record to supply accurate pricing data.

Possible Solutions: Final pricing file available on ____ day after month-end.
Hedge Fund pricing and use of prior period and restatement.
Other pricing issues.

Incorrectly valued asset receipts and deliveries.: These need to be valued and representative of the value of the asset in the month the receipt/delivery occurs. If the book/carry value of the asset is provided to First Rate, the result will be a large gain or loss for the period and skewed return.

None: Client posts all receipts/deliveries with current value.
Client will create extract change that performs valuation.
Client requests First Rate to revalue using the following pricing scheme.
Capital Gains posting on the day following a price drop.: This is a problem for daily portfolios and if it happens at the end of a month it could be a problem for monthly portfolios too.

None: Move the day the transaction occurs in First Rate Performance.
Change the day of the price change.

Corporate Action Spin-offs that result in part of the old asset funding an asset in a new performance segment.: If the trades aren't present to fund the new asset and divest a portion of the old asset, there are performance issues.

None: Client will pass trades that reduce position in old asset and fund new asset.
Client requests that First Rate create custom program that creates trades based on file of corporate action cusips. Detail in Business analysis phase.

A cusip changes IDs and sectors.: The process we use should reflect what is on the trust system. In many cases, no transactions are utilized for the removal of the old asset and the arrival of the new asset.

None: Client will provide Free Delivery transaction at value for the old asset and a Free Receipt transaction for the new asset using the same value for that day.
Client requests First Rate create custom program that creates delivery and receipt transactions.
Cause of Inaccurate Returns: Income or Fee Rebates are not tied to an asset. This impacts Total Fund and will not be attributed to the manager or asset earning income.

Possible Solutions: Assign security ID to transaction on extract.
Let it post as income to Cash/Total Fund.
None: Units without Value or Value with zero units on a holding. Both conditions could be indicator of inaccurate performance.

None: Send prices and have program written to revalue assets accordingly.
Test extract to ensure that problem does not exist.

Auditing Month-to-Date Performance: First Rate conducts a daily review to determine if inbound files were received and loaded into the performance system. If there are issues involving the data, First Rate will notify the client to discuss issues impacting the process. Month-to-date returns are considered preliminary and therefore should be used as such.

None: First Rate will refrain from repairing month-to-date data as transactions are typically being revised, repaired, and corrected for any given month up until three business days after a month-end. This practice prevents making edits that may be impacted by a subsequent data. If your organization requires something other than this standard service level, please discuss those requirements with your sales representative.

Auditing Daily Returns: In the event of a significant cash flow, the performance industry recommends that the portfolio be revalued and a return calculated on the day of the flow. For clients providing daily prices, asset coupon rates, and income payment dates, First Rate will compute daily returns in order to achieve a more accurate one month return for reporting.

None: First Rate reviews the resulting monthly return after the end of the month. If the result of the daily returns is a monthly return that falls outside the tolerances set by the client, then the daily returns will be reviewed for price and accrual issues.
None: Accounting data is the only data reviewed to determine accuracy of daily returns. Daily returns themselves are not reviewed for reasonability unless there is a problem with the monthly return.

Release of Final Audited Prior Month Performance: With a good extract / interface process that supplies accurate accounting data, the client can usually expect 90 – 95% of their portfolios to be available for preliminary viewing within 24 hours of receipt of the last files (i.e., prices and backdated trades) necessary to compute the prior month performance. It can take anywhere from another one to seven business days to resolve all the issues for the remaining portfolios. Typically, another 2 – 3% of the portfolios are released on the 4th and 5th business days based on global accounting repairs.

First Rate Performance displays a status code on each portfolio to indicate its status for prior month performance. Initially, portfolios that pass all exception reports will show Preliminary status until global audits are completed. At that point, they will be adjusted to display Final status. If a portfolio appears on an exception report, it will show an In Review status until all corrections are made or the return is deemed correct.

Typically, First Rate releases preliminary portfolios immediately to Advisor and the portfolios being reviewed are made available as they are scrubbed and finalized. The availability of these portfolios in Advisor is controlled by a report that may be set according to the method of releasing accounts:

• Release as returns are reviewed / revised
• Release altogether
• Other

First Rate’s Standard Auditing Process: As a practice, all revisions to accounting data are confirmed by the client and noted in our audit logs at the time of repair or in the monthly archived copy of the audit reports that describe the issue. Over time, the client and performance analyst may agree on a set of standard audit practices in order to expedite delivery and avoid case-by-case approval. These will be noted in the client’s checklist.
Accounting Data Review: The following accounting data is reviewed:

Units Out of Balance (UOOB): Balances for beginning and ending units for all positions reconciled with all transactions that impact units. Units Out of Balance can be an indicator of a missing trade, missing transaction code, or an improperly classified transaction code. Or it could be an old asset changing its identifier; the old asset is left with no current units but units in the prior time period. Conversely, the new asset identifier will have units at the current time frameand no previous units for the prior time period. In both cases, no transaction will be received from the trust system to account for the asset changes.

Note that if you wish to exclude cash assets from the UOOB report, you can either flag them individually for exclusion or flag the entire cash sector and set a global variable that allows you to ‘Skip UOOB logging for the &CASH sector’.

Cash Out of Balance (COOB): Balances for beginning and ending cash positions reconciled with transactions that impact cash. Cash out of Balance can be an indicator of a missing transaction, missing transaction code, or an improper transaction code. This could also be a result of a backdated trade that impacted a previous month, along with the cash balance of the portfolio for that previous month. In many cases this would also impact UOOB if the backdated trade involves a buy or sale of an asset.
No Transaction Code: Client has passed a new transaction code that has no performance effects defined.
Sector Change Audit: Find holdings moving from one sector to another. Client confirms that these changes are intended and they are reversed if necessary.
No Sector Audit: Finds holdings that have no sectors assigned, and therefore aren't impacting performance as they should.

Asset Summary Review: Displays detailed asset-level data for selected portfolios and dates, including more than a dozen linked audit reports. Look for asset-level return issues such as different asset versus price returns, returns out of tolerance, missing prices, and so forth.
Invalid Transaction Principal Report: Identifies Free Receipt (FR) and Free Delivery (FD) transactions as decided by clients with potential pricing issues.
Price Warnings: Identifies specific assets that can cause return review exceptions. Also identifies assets that are not priced or have bad prices.
Return Review: Returns are reviewed as follows:
Return Review: The Rate Distribution and Rate Warnings reports are used when reviewing monthly return quality after accounting data has been repaired.

Return Tolerances: The tighter the tolerance level, the longer it takes to review returns because more valid returns appear on the report and must be reviewed. Conversely, there may be some returns that pass tolerance, but are not technically correct. First Rate recommends that rate tolerances start at:
• 7% above or below a market index for equities
• 3% above or below for a fixed income index
• 0.5% above or below for a short-term index

Tolerance Packages: First Rate lets you create and assign tolerance packages to individual portfolios or portfolio groups. These packages establish an acceptable high and low return range for selected sectors, categories, and currencies relative to a benchmark or a flat return (i.e., no benchmark assigned). Portfolios of rates of return falling outside the established tolerance appear on the Rate Warnings report, allowing you to spot exceptions. This requires each portfolio’s investment objective to be passed to First Rate and appropriate benchmarks selected for processing. If this is not available, a default tolerance package will be applied.

Pricing Source: First Rate uses the client's prices exclusively as the pricing source. While we do not verify every price separately, reviewing the Price Warnings and Invalid Transaction Principal reports may reveal an invalid price for receipts/deliveries being valued, corporate actions, or a capital gains issue.

Performance Segment Return Review: Option 1 – All segment / category returns are reviewed for reasonableness. In order to implement this option, a benchmark must be assigned for each performance segment that adequately reflects the returns that should be expected and reflects the tolerance for each portfolio. The Rate Distribution report can give you an indication of the data quality without benchmarks.
Option 2 – First Rate computes as many performance segments as desired and reviews them at a high level for
reasonableness. An example might involve Total Equity, Total Fixed, Total Cash, and Cash Equivalents.

Composites:

Overview: Composites are created and maintained in First Rate Performance. In most cases, the terms composite and aggregate may be used interchangeably, as composites are generally handled the same as aggregates in First Rate Performance.
The composite function allows you to create a portfolio with rates of return representative of a group of portfolios. You can create composites as Asset Weighted (beginning period asset weighting) or Super Composites.
You may control a portfolio's participation in a composite by specifying starting and ending dates in the Participation Dates Editor. Portfolios can move in and out of composites multiple times or participate in multiple composites, based on changes in Investment objectives or other criteria.
Your First Rate implementation team will ask questions to clarify your needs for composites.

Asset Weighted Composites: Asset Weighted Composites are most commonly used for strategy composites when the intent is to measure the average return of a set of accounts with the same strategy or investment objective. The purpose of aggregating the sub-accounts as an asset weighted composite is to focus on the manager's performance. The formula for Asset Weighted composites is:
((UVR*ABMV)+(UVR*ABMV))
Total ABMV
Where ABMV represents the Adjusted Beginning Market Value computed as:
ABMV =
(EMV + EA + 1) - ((1 - PF)P + (1 - NF)N)
UVR
Super Composites: Super Composites are typically used for relationship composites when the intent is to measure the return for all the family assets and the focus is on asset growth.
Super Composites are computed by applying the Modified Dietz to the summed financials of all the underlying sub-accounts.

Separately Managed Account (SMA) Composites: First Rate Performance allows you to designate composites as Separately Managed Account (SMA) composite types. A Separately Managed Account composite is an investment vehicle whereby an investment institution outsources portfolio management to an external firm that specializes in a particular style of investing (i.e., Large Cap Growth). These managers have total discretion over a portion of the investor's money and all investment decisions are viewed as being managed in the style.
An important advantage of this type of account is that it provides investors with a multitude of experts instead of being limited to a single institution's expertise. The SMA also provides clients with certain tax advantages, such as avoiding unearned capital gains associated with mutual funds or being able to direct investment managers to sell certain assets for tax purposes.
For investment firms, SMAs allows them to market the types of composites they are good at managing and hire outside experts to do the rest. If an investment manager does poorly, they can shift the money to another manager while still retaining the relationship with the investor.

Unified Managed Account (UMA) Composites: UMAs are accounts that have separate managers, but all holdings and models are contained in one account. There are some benefits to the account holder, i.e. lower cost to access outside managers, lower operational overhead, scalable investment process, and tax optimization. The challenge in this type of account is that it becomes difficult to track individual manager performance, which is important in the evaluation. For this type of account, a UMA vendor separates the accounts into sleeves or sub-accounts which are then loaded into First Rate as accounts; in this manner, each manager can be tracked at multiple levels and manager models can be mimicked more easily. The sleeves (accounts) are then aggregated back together to provide the performance for the UMA.

There are two approaches to UMA management: optimization approach and manager replication approach. The optimization approach seeks to report the tax benefit of the UMA in total. While there are fewer sleeves (accounts) to reconcile, there is a loss of transparency of each manager and it is difficult to decompose the effects of managers on client performance. The manager replication approach provides more transparency by manager but requires more accounting. The type of reporting approach should align with the value proposition of the investment firm.

ACE Composites: First Rate Performance provides an Automated Composite Engine (ACE) that automatically manages the movement of composite constituents based on client-defined sets of business rules. Movement in and out of ACE composites is done through ACE Lights Out batches that build composite performance and update portfolio participation dates.

Rules are defined and grouped together as a rules package. The rules package is assigned to a composite account. The composite must have the aggregate type of “ACE” assigned in order to be included in the nightly batch ACE jobs.

The ACE functionality provides several benefits for clients, including that it:

• Minimizes the chances of human error that can occur with composite management.
• Provides security-controlled access by your First Rate administrator.

Manages portfolio participation by defining specific business rules for
composite membership.
Integrates performance with a composite management tool.

Provides management and audit reports that are helpful in the GIPS
verification process.

Composite Constituent Changes Report: provides a list of portfolios

GIPS Compliance
Global Performance

The CFA Institute has developed a set of guidelines for presenting performance
calculations to the public. These guidelines are officially known as Global
Investment Performance Standards (GIPS).

The CFA Institute does not provide guidelines for performance calculation
software; the GIPS guidelines apply only to investment firms. As a result, a
performance measurement application cannot claim to be GIPS compliant.

The GIPS guidelines specify several requirements in order for an investment
management firm to claim GIPS compliance. All assets under the management
of the firm must meet all of the GIPS requirements. For example, GIPS

guidelines specify which methodologies may be used to calculate a rate of return
for an individual portfolio or composite.

First Rate Performance uses calculations that adhere to GIPS guidelines for
calculation methodology. Calculation requirements include::

• Total returns must include income and realized/unrealized gains and
losses.
• A time-weighted rate of return must be used, or an appropriate
approximation, including a minimum of monthly valuations and adjusting
for cash flows. Interim returns must be geometrically linked.
• Values used to calculate rates of return for fixed income securities must
include accrued income.
• Composites must be asset-weighted using beginning-of-period weightings
or another method that reflects both beginning value and cash flows.
• Returns from cash and cash equivalents held in portfolios must be
included in total-return calculations.
• Performance must be calculated after the deduction of all trading
expenses.
• If a firm sets a minimum asset level for portfolios to be included in a
composite, no portfolios below that asset level can be included in the
composite.

First Rate Performance provides the tools needed to abide by each of these
calculation methodology requirements, however, following the requirements does
not automatically qualify a firm as GIPS-compliant.

Accrual and Cash Accounting: GIPS requires accrual accounting for fixed income assets and recommends
accrual accounting on equity assets with dividends. First Rate prefers to get
accrual information from the accounting system of record, but we can provide
custom modules if necessary. You have the option to report values that include
or exclude accruals in the total value.

Settlement and Trade Date Performance: Since January 1, 2005, GIPS has recommended that performance be calculated
on a trade date basis. If you are currently calculating all or some of your
portfolios on the settlement date, you can move to the trade date as of your

conversion date. Or, you can designate a date like the beginning of the year or
calendar quarter.

If your current performance is on a settlement date basis and you are switching
to trade date performance, you will have additional crossover issues to consider.
Your bridge into First Rate Performance will need to be designed so that the first
month of trade date performance includes what would have been traded in the
prior month but not posted in the new month.

First Rate Consulting also offers custom programming that will backdate trades
from the current month into the prior month of performance. First Rate does not
recommend backdating performance more than one month prior to the current
month as this restates published returns and the cost to roll these restatements
thru the future stored positions and transactions would outweigh the benefit.

For example, if your first month of performance of trade date is May, the bridge
for May would need to pick up all pending trades as of April 30th. In other words,
an April 30th trade that settled on May 2nd would appear as a trade on May 1st
which is as close to April as the performance system can get without backdating
the trades to a prior month and adjusting holdings.

Trade Date Performance from Settlement Date Extracts: It is possible within the First Rate interface with the accounting system to adjust
settlement date holdings based on trade date trades. This can be achieved in
two ways depending upon the timing requirement for delivering performance
data.

Creating Trade Date Performance Based on Pending Trades: If preliminary performance is required prior to the fourth business day of the
month, the client should send clearly identified pending purchases and sales as
of the performance month-end either in the transaction extract or in a separate
feed. First Rate will adjust the cash and holdings based on those pending
trades. The transaction will also be identified as a pending trade for further use.
When the trade settles in the following month, it should also be sent in the extract
with the original trade date (prior month) and settlement date. First Rate will
reverse the original pending trade or delete it and repost the trade with the
settled amount. If a trade is missed in the original monthly extract and is entered
with a trade date in the prior month, it will be processed in the prior month if it is a
purchase or a sale.
Portfolios with prior month trades will have performance for that prior month
rebuilt and restated. A report is available that lists trades for the prior month and
those that are posted further back than the prior month. In the event that trades
go back further than one month, they will be posted to the first date of the current month and identified on that report for further consideration, based on client input.

If the client requires that prior month performance not be adjusted, then the pending trade from the prior month must be reversed in the following month when the settlement trade is received in order to prevent double counting of a trade in performance.

Creating Trade Date Performance from Settled Trades: If preliminary performance reporting can be held until after the third business day, you may want to create trade date performance from settled trades. Since the majority of purchases and sale trades settle within three business days, the client could also elect to hold their extract until the evening of the third business day. On the transaction file, they can pass the performance month’s trades (first of the month) plus the trades that occur in the first three business days of the next month. Each monthly transaction file is sent with all transactions that settle from the first of the performance month to the third of the following month.
The trades that settle in the first three business days of the following month that have trade dates prior to that month are used to create trade date adjusted cash and holding records.
To prevent including those trades again in the following month, First Rate Performance uses a Prior Month Cut Date variable to identify trades already included through that prior performance month. Any trades that settled after the cut date but traded in the prior month are dated the first day of the new month, prior month holdings and cash are not adjusted.

Benchmarks: In First Rate Performance, you can maintain a variety of different benchmarks for reporting, auditing, and comparison purposes. Benchmarks provide a standard against which you can measure performance for an asset, benchmark, or investor. First Rate Performance uses the following types of benchmarks:

Market benchmarks
Blended benchmarks
Target Policy benchmarks

Market Benchmarks: You may maintain a variety of benchmarks in your database. A market
benchmark can be linked to a specific sector or category so that when you run
reports, the associated benchmark is selected. Examples of market benchmarks
include the S&P 500, Russell 2000 Growth Index, 90 Day T-Bill, and so forth.
Additionally, First Rate maintains a subscription with many benchmark services
that make benchmarks available through a separate agreement. Please speak
with your First Rate representative to obtain additional information on this
service.
Fund returns may also be used as a benchmark.

Blended (Portfolio-Specific) Benchmarks: First Rate Performance allows you to create a custom or blended benchmark that
combines an unlimited number of market benchmarks. Blended benchmarks
provide a dynamic, portfolio-specific mix of benchmarks that use one or all of the
portfolio's sectors.
When defining blended benchmarks, the institution associates the portfolio's
performance segments (i.e., asset class, style, or sector) with benchmarks. The
benchmark's contribution will be based on the percentage of the performance
segment's adjusted beginning balance to the sum of all beginning balances of
the segments included in the benchmark definition.
There are two types of blended benchmarks:

• Asset-Weighted Blended Benchmark – This dynamic blend is specific to
the actual allocation of each portfolio. The asset-weighted blend can contain
an unlimited number of sector-benchmark associations. These benchmarks
remove the weight variances between the portfolio segments and their
benchmarks to provide an overall “stock picking return variance”

• Policy-Weighted Blended Benchmark – This static blend is based on a
stated policy of diversification and is often defined at the institutional level.
The policy-weighted blend can contain up to 20 benchmarks. The total
weighting of all constituent benchmarks must be 100. Policies are provided to
First Rate and the static blend is computed.
For both types of blended benchmarks, changes can be made over time,
historic assignments will be maintained and will be used in the case of
rebuilds.

Target Policy Benchmarks: First Rate Performance lets you create a portfolio-level investment policy, or
target policy, that determines how portfolio assets should be allocated. The
target policy specifies the sectors in which portfolio funds are invested, the
benchmarks to which sector performance is compared, the percentage of
portfolio funds that are allocated to each sector (from 0 to 100 inclusive), and the
minimum and maximum allowable policy variances.

You can also specify sector-benchmark mappings with zero percent policy

Benchmark Reporting: Depending on the level of control an institution wants to apply, benchmark assignments can be managed in First Rate Advisor using the following methods:

Portfolio Default / Benchmark Packaging – Portfolio Default allows an individual benchmark or benchmark package to be assigned at the portfolio level. When an end user chooses Portfolio Default in First Rate Advisor, that benchmark or group of benchmarks displays on designated reports. This functionality allows clients to ensure that a prescribed benchmark is always reported for that portfolio. The Portfolio Default may be combined with other benchmark reporting methods.

A Benchmark Package allows a user to group one or more benchmarks of any type (i.e., market, policy, or blended) into a package and assign that package to a portfolio in First Rate Professional. Samples of benchmark packages include:

Single Benchmark Package – Market Index – A managed portfolio may be compared to a single benchmark. If First Rate Advisor must always use a particular benchmark when that portfolio is reported, the package may contain a single benchmark.
Single Benchmark Package – Benchmark – At other times for a balanced portfolio there may be a dynamic benchmark, policy benchmark, and component market benchmarks suitable for the package.

Multi-Benchmark Package – A client may use a mix of these two types of packages. Particularly with a Separately Managed Account (SMA), the individual component portfolios may have single benchmark packages while the relationship or composite has a multi-benchmark package.
Benchmark Groups – Individual users or an administrator can create groups of benchmarks and make them available to First Rate Advisor users for reporting.

Ad Hoc Benchmarks – This optional feature can be used at run-time to select the set of benchmarks desired for that reporting session. The report(s) will ignore the benchmark group or portfolio default group previously selected.
Portfolio Benchmarks – Any portfolio, composite, or model portfolio tracked on the accounting system can be used as a benchmark for attribution analysis.
Target Policy Benchmarks – If a portfolio has been assigned a target policy in First Rate Professional, certain reports in First Rate Advisor use

the target policy benchmark table to determine which benchmarks to
include. Benchmarks appear following their associated sector or category.

Partial Month Benchmarks: When your reporting period includes either
partial starting months (due to portfolio inception dates) or partial ending
months (due to the As of Date), certain First Rate Advisor reports link daily
benchmark returns to create partial-month benchmarks. This occurs only
when daily benchmark returns are available for the entire reporting period;
daily and monthly data cannot be mixed together.

If you have daily benchmarks without history but there is monthly history
available, you can run a program (FRPINDM2D) to load monthly returns to
the daily benchmark returns table for the month-end date.

Reporting: Reporting Overview
At First Rate, we understand that the reports you deliver provide evidence of your service and illustrate your investment story to your clients. First Rate Advisor has over ninety reports available for reviewing, analyzing, and presenting performance information, including:
• Performance Reports – Over 70 classic reports that are part of First Rate Advisor’s standard offering.
• Analyst Reports – Package of premium reports for back-office analysts, available as a separately negotiated license.

• OnPoint Reports – Personalized reports consisting of base sub-report components, various templates, and a client-branded theme, created through First Rate Administration’s wizard-driven interface. These reports can be run on an ad-hoc basis in First Rate Advisor or organized into report groups and scheduled to run for specific portfolio groups.

First Rate’s reports provide different levels of performance granularity to meet your client needs. Using Advisor’s decision-making guide, the Field Guide to Reporting, the First Rate implementation team will review the available Advisor reports with you to confirm which reports you want to use and the data necessary to support them.

On a functional level, running reports is the culmination of many decisions made during the Advisor setup process. During the implementation process, you will have the opportunity to determine how to customize the Advisor application for optimal use. Aside from report selection, some of the flexible features include:
• Creating groups for reporting purposes.
• Creating Quick Select portfolio groups.
• Assigning portfolio, sector, and benchmark graph colors.
• Managing report date options.
• Making time period and sector selections.
• Using Tiered Reporting and/or Managed Reporting.

Creating Groups: First Rate Performance lets you set up groups to help you process performance or run reports. Groups are collections of items used when reviewing Quick View data or running reports. When you initially log onto the application, you must first set up at least one portfolio group before running reports or reviewing Quick View data.

Use the Personalize tab in First Rate Advisor to set up groups. Depending on your security privileges, you may be able to add and maintain the following types of groups:
Portfolio groups: Use Personalize -> My Portfolios to manage your assigned portfolios into folder groups. These groups of portfolios appear on Advisor's Summary and Run Reports pages.

Report groups: Use Personalize -> My Reports to add, remove, and update groups of reports that are run on the Run Reports page. The report group remembers which reports to run, the sort order, and the various options and sectors so you do not have to re-set your preferences each time to run a report. This results in better consistency and productivity.

Report Option groups: Use Personalize -> Custom Options to add, remove, and update report option groups that are used to set up report groups. Option groups specify how many periods you wish to report on, which reporting frequencies, which sector schemas, and so forth. Option groups appear on the Run Reports and My Reports pages

Sector and Benchmark groups: Use Personalize -> Custom Benchmarks or Custom Sectors to add and manage sector or benchmark groups that are used to set up report groups. Sector and Benchmark groups appear on the Run Reports My Reports pages.

Report Option 2 groups: Secondary report option groups appear in the Custom Report Options 2 window on the Run Reports and My Reports pages. Accessible from the hyperlinked report name, report option 2 groups establish additional run-time parameters. Care should be taken so that the default for all other users does not change; instead, create a new RO2 group to make changes for your own reports.

Sector Benchmark Sort groups: Use Personalize -> Sector Benchmark Sort to manage how sectors and benchmarks are sorted when running reports or viewing Quick View data. Sector benchmark sort groups appear in the Custom Report Options 2 window on the Run Reports and My Reports pages.
Groups provide a lot of flexibility. For example, when adding a group of reports, you can add the same report twice, assigning each instance of the report a different group of report options.

Creating Quick Select Portfolio Groups: Advisor’s Quick Select Portfolio Groups let you create adhoc portfolio groups from the Summary page without using Personalize -> My Portfolios. This improves the speed of group building and data retrieval. Once populated, these Quick Select groups appear at the top of your list of portfolio groups on both the Summary and Run Reports page. Access to this feature is controlled by your administrator.
The Quick Select drop-down menu provides the following portfolio options:

['Quick Select Single Portfolio – Select a single portfolio by name or ID.', 'Quick Select Static List – Select multiple portfolios by ID.', 'Quick Select Dynamic List – Select multiple portfolios by filter values.', 'My Composites – Create and build permanent or temporary composites from existing portfolio groups.']

Assigning Graph Colors: First Rate Professional lets you customize the graph colors assigned to portfolios, sectors, and benchmarks for reporting purposes. These selections are stored in the color fields of the portfolio demographics and sector/benchmark tables and utilized by Advisor when running presentations.
First Rate Administration also lets you select graph colors for data that is not sector/benchmark specific, such as portfolio data, model data, and the All Other group. These color selections are stored in the global variables table.
If colors are not specified in the above tables, First Rate Performance uses the default colors from the system-wide color scheme.
You may also run a color assignment program from Lights Out to automatically generate colors for portfolios, sectors, and benchmarks that have missing colors. This program is intended to be run once or for large quantities of missing colors, not on a regular basis. This is because new missing colors will always be assigned the first colors from the file.
Managing Report Date Options: First Rate Performance provides several global options that allow you to manage how report dates are displayed and reported. A few of these options include:
Report Date Options: Controls whether the From date on presentation and drill-down reports uses the last day of the prior month or the first day of the month.

Last Load Date: Controls the last As of Date permitted on the Quick View, Run Reports, and Managed Reporting screens, based upon the date of the last data load. For example, if the last load date is 11/15/11, First Rate Performance will allow As of Dates from 11/1/11 through 11/15/11 or any month-end date for the previous month (i.e., 10/31/11, 09/30/11, etc.).

Date Format Elections: Controls whether the application, presentation, and drill-down reports use the MM/DD/YYYY or DD/MM/YYYY date format. In addition, you may select the calendar phrase ‘As of Date’ or ‘As at Date’.

Build Freeze Dates: The portfolio build freeze date limits how far back performance can be built for individual portfolios. The global build freeze date limits how far back any performance data can be build.

Making Time and Sector Selections: First Rate Advisor has a dynamic user interface that allows you to produce reports on an adh oc or scheduled basis. Most reports can be selected to run at a sector or category level and for user-defined time periods. During the implementation process, your team will explain all flexible options and determine the best definition and roll-out for your organization.

Using Tiered Reporting: First Rate offers Tiered Reporting to clients who are interested in providing differing levels of report access to their customers. When tiered reporting is enabled, tier levels are assigned to sectors, categories, reports, and portfolios. When your First Rate Advisor users run reports, portfolios are restricted to reports and sectors/categories that are within the portfolio’s assigned tier level. If tiered reporting interests you, please inform your First Rate implementation team.

Using Managed Reporting: While the Summary and Run Reports pages provide access to portfolio
information in drill-down and presentation reports, the Managed Reporting page
provides volume reporting for large numbers of portfolios.
With authorization, users can associate report and portfolio groups and save
these associations for use later, even with other user's groups. The portfolio
groups used in managed reporting are specific to managed reporting and do not
appear on the Summary and Run Reports pages, although you can use regular
portfolio groups with managed reporting.
Managed Reporting includes granular security at several levels to control access
to managed reporting output, tools for building managed reporting groups, and
other user's groups. Your First Rate implementation team will discuss your
Managed Reporting options.

Branding: You may elect to have your institution's logo appear on reports. Your First Rate
representative can provide you with the exact image specifications. If there are
multiple groups at your institution with different logo requirements, First Rate will
work with you to develop a custom process to assign the logos properly.
In addition to using custom logos in presentations, First Rate Advisor lets you
change the application name itself by:
Replacing all occurrences of "First Rate Advisor" with your application
name, except in the copyright statements.
Replace all images in the application and online help that include the
application name.
Use a splash page with custom content.
Branding does not include changing First Rate Advisor's color theme or style
sheets. For information on customizing the product beyond branding, please
contact your First Rate representative.

Advisor Express: Overview
Advisor Express is an enhanced front-end product for First Rate Advisor that provides users with quick, easy access to portfolio research and performance reports. Upon logging into Advisor Express, authorized users may click a portfolio ID or filter the displayed portfolios to view associated reporting information.
The right pane of Advisor Express provides the following tabbed data:

• Point-to-Point Tab – Provides monthly and partial-month daily returns for two user-supplied dates. Click the links to generate the Holdings (Values) Listing or Transaction Listing reports for the selected date range.

• Returns Tab – Provides value and return data for the default sector group for month-to-date, 3 month, year-to-date, or inception-to-date time periods. Click the links to generate the Sector Detail (Master Listing) or Returns (Portfolio Listing) reports.

• Allocation Tab – Displays a value allocation pie graph for the selected portfolio. Click any pie piece to view a sector and value listing, or drill down to the sector, asset, and ticker levels if desired.
The left pane of Advisor Express provides links to the following reports:
• Portfolio Statement – Generates a portfolio statement for the selected As of Date or runs any Advisor report group for the selected As of Date and benchmark group.
• Selected Group Reporting – Generates a Master Performance Listing for a group of portfolios based on selected filter values.

Implement portfolio security

Set up Advisor Express global variables
